    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA19-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu puṇarntu nīṅkiya talaivaṉait tōḻi varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante asked HIM for marriage when he left after the union.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA19">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iṟavuppuṟat taṉṉa piṇarpaṭu taṭavumutaṟ</l>
<l>            cuṟavukkōṭ ṭaṉṉa muḷḷilait tāḻai</l>
<l>            peruṅkaḷiṟṟu maruppi ṉaṉṉa varumpumutirpu </l>
<l>            naṉmā ṉuḷaiyiṉ vēṟupaṭat tōṉṟi</l>
<l>            viḻavukkaḷaṅ kamaḻu muravunīrc cērppa </l>
<l>            viṉamaṇi neṭuntēr pāka ṉiyakkac</l>
<l>            celīiya cēṟi yāyi ṉivaḷē</l>
<l>            varuvai yākiya ciṉṉāḷ</l>
<l>            vāḻā ḷātaṉaṟ kaṟintaṉai ceṉmē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O man from the coast of the strong water,</l>
<l rend="indent3">which smells [like] a festival ground,</l>
<l rend="indent2">since the buds, like the tusks of a big elephant bull, have ripened,</l>
<l rend="indent2">appearing to change [in colour?] like the mane of a good horse,<note place="foot">Thus the suggestion made by Th.A., but still the impact of the line is not quite clear.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">on the Tāḻai trees with leaves thorny like a swordfish's horn<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cuṟavu</term> is, according to the lexica, mostly both "shark" and "swordfish", and supposedly so because of passages like this one, and at least the conjecture makes sense.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] a broad base becoming rough like prawns' backs,</l>
<l>– if you are going to go,</l>
<l>while the charioteer urges the long chariot with different<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iṉam maṇi</term>: here word order is significant, i.e. not "a group of bells" (which would be <term xml:lang="ta">maṇi y-iṇar</term>), but, according to tradition, "different kinds of bells".</note> bells [forward],</l>
<l rend="indent3">as for her,</l>
<l>go as one who has understood well that she would not live<note place="foot">Here the variant contains the positive form <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻvāḷ</term>, which presumably conveys the same message in a slightly veiled form: "that she would live [only] few days until you come".</note></l>
<l rend="indent">the few days until<note place="foot">How precisely to account for the <term xml:lang="ta">ākiya</term> here? It is certainy used as an embedding verb in order to integrate the aspect- and personal mark of the finite form <term xml:lang="ta">varuvai</term> ("the few days that are the ‘you will come’[-days]").</note> you come.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
